    "ArticleTitle": "Amplification-free RNA detection with CRISPR-Cas13.",
    "Pagination": {
      "StartPage": "476",
      "MedlinePgn": "476"
    },
    "Abstract": {
      "AbstractText": [
        "CRISPR-based nucleic-acid detection is an emerging technology for molecular diagnostics. However, these methods generally require several hours and could cause amplification errors, due to the pre-amplification of target nucleic acids to enhance the detection sensitivity. Here, we developed a platform that allows \"CRISPR-based amplification-free digital RNA detection (SATORI)\", by combining CRISPR-Cas13-based RNA detection and microchamber-array technologies. SATORI detected single-stranded RNA targets with maximal sensitivity of ~10 fM in <5\u2009min, with high specificity. Furthermore, the simultaneous use of multiple different guide RNAs enhanced the sensitivity, thereby enabling the detection of the SARS-CoV-2 N-gene RNA at ~5 fM levels. Therefore, we hope\u00a0SATORI will serve as a powerful class of accurate and rapid diagnostics."
      ]
    },
